POETICAL
AVIART.

From
me
no
secret
he
can
hide,

I
see
his
vanity
and
pride.

And
my
delight
is
to
expose

His
follies
to
his
greatest
foes.

All
languages
I
can
command,

Yet
not
a
word
I
understand.

Without
my
aid
the
best
divine

In
learning
would
not
know
a
fine.

The
lawyer
must
forget
his
pleading,

The
scholar
could
not
show
his
reading.

Nay
man,
my
master,
is
my
slave,

*
I
give
command
to
kill
or
save.

Can
grant
ten
thousand
pounds
a
year,

And
make
a
beggar's
brat
a
peer.

But
while
I
thus
my
life
relate,

I
only
hasten
to
my
fate.

My
tongue
is
black,
my
mouth
is
furred,

I
hardly
now
can
force
a
word.

I
die
unpitied
and
forgot,

And
on
some
dunghill
left
to
rot.

The
notice
of
Ben
Jonson's
"
learned
sock"
has
contributed

to
the
common
notion
that
we
are
not
to
look
to
him
for
lyric

graces.
This
however,
is
a
very
erroneous
opinion.
With

some
assistance
from
Martial,
he
has
done
justice
to
the

softness
and
sweetness
which
we
owe
to
the
winged
creation

independently
of
our
eyes
and
ears.

Have
you
seen
but
a
bright
lily
grow,

Before
rude
hands
have
touch'd
it
?

Have
you
marked
but
the
fall
of
the
snow,

Before
the
soil
hath
smutch'd
it
?

Have
you
felt
the
wool
of
the
beaver
?

Or
Swans-down
ever
?

Or
have
smelt
of
the
bud
of
the
brier
?

Or
the
nard
in
the
fire
?

Or
have
tasted
the
bag
of
the
bee
?

O !
so
white
!
O,
so
soft
!
O,
so
sweet
is
she.
